<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-07-11T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-07-11T23:00:00-05:00" n="418" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d418">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.003/632: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Ruddock</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-07-12T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">July 12,
                                        1921—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received July 12—6:55
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>256. Your 157, June 28th [<hi rend="italic">26th</hi>], 6 p.m.,
                                1920.<note n="76" xml:id="d418fn76"><ref target="frus1920v01#pg_735"><hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 735</ref>.</note> Chinese
                            Government now requests Governments concerned to proceed in perfect
                            accord with second revision of customs schedule to effective 5 percent
                            as provided by commission of 1918. No reference made to likin
                            abolition.</p>
                        <p>Request authorization indicate assent if other powers agree.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Ruddock</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>